Review of hypercerts-nyk.15 found an overly broad CSS selector in lib/atproto-branding.ts.

Lines 94-95 and 120-123:
```css
img[alt="Hypercerts Logo"],
img[alt*="Logo"] {   /* matches ANY image whose alt contains 'Logo' */
  width: 200px !important;
  height: 40px !important;
  ...
}

@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  img[alt="Hypercerts Logo"],
  img[alt*="Logo"] {
    filter: invert(1) !important;  /* inverts ALL such images */
  }
}
```

The `img[alt*="Logo"]` substring selector will match any image on the PDS OAuth pages whose alt text contains the word 'Logo' (case-sensitive). This could accidentally resize and invert partner logos, app icons, or any future image the PDS adds with 'Logo' in its alt text.

The intent is clearly to target only the Hypercerts app logo. The more specific `img[alt="Hypercerts Logo"]` selector already covers the exact target.

Evidence: lib/atproto-branding.ts lines 94-104 and 119-127.

Fix: Remove the `img[alt*="Logo"]` fallback selector from both the base rule and the dark mode rule. Keep only `img[alt="Hypercerts Logo"]`. If the PDS uses a different exact alt text, add that specific value instead of a substring match.

Review of hypercerts-nyk.15 found an unnecessary CSS rule in lib/atproto-branding.ts.

Line 232-234:
```css
main.flex.flex-col.items-center > h1.text-primary {
  position: relative !important;
}
```

This `position: relative` is set to enable the `::before` pseudo-element logo. However, the `::before` pseudo-element (lines 236-246) uses `display: block` with `margin: 0 auto 24px auto` — it is in normal block flow, not absolutely positioned. A `position: relative` parent is only needed for `position: absolute` children. Since the `::before` is block-flow, the `position: relative` on the parent has no effect.

Evidence: lib/atproto-branding.ts lines 232-246. The ::before pseudo-element has no `position: absolute` or `position: fixed`.

Fix: Remove the `position: relative !important` rule from `main.flex.flex-col.items-center > h1.text-primary`. This also allows merging the two split rule blocks for this selector (lines 232-234 and 258-261) into one.

